SIMPLE: stain
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stain
<hw>Stain</hw> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Stained</conjf> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧nd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr.
& vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Staining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Abbrev. fr.
<ets>distain</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To discolor by the
application of foreign matter; to make foul; to spot; <as>as, to
<ex>stain</ex> the hand with dye; armor <ex>stained</ex> with
blood</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To color, as wood, glass, paper, cloth, or the like,
by processes affecting, chemically or otherwise, the material itself; to
tinge with a color or colors combining with, or penetrating, the
substance; to dye; <as>as, to <ex>stain</ex> wood with acids, colored
washes, paint rubbed in, etc.; to <ex>stain</ex> glass</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To spot with guilt or infamy; to bring reproach on;
to blot; to soil; to tarnish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of honor void,⟦br⟧
Of innocence, of faith, of purity,⟦br⟧
Our wonted ornaments now soiled and <qex>stained</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To cause to seem inferior or soiled by
comparison.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She <qex>stains</qex> the ripest virgins of her age.</q>
<rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That did all other beasts in beauty <qex>stain</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stained glass</b></col>, <cd>glass colored or stained by
certain metallic pigments fused into its substance, -- often used for
making ornamental windows.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To paint; dye; blot; soil; sully; discolor;
disgrace; taint.</syn> -- <usage><er>Paint</er>, <er>Stain</er>,
<er>Dye</er>. These denote three different processes; the first
mechanical, the other two, chiefly chemical. To <xex>paint</xex> a thing
is to spread a coat of coloring matter over it; to <xex>stain</xex> or
<xex>dye</xex> a thing is to impart color to its substance. To
<xex>stain</xex> is said chiefly of solids, as wood, glass, paper; to
<xex>dye</xex>, of fibrous substances, textile fabrics, etc.; the one,
commonly, a simple process, as applying a wash; the other more complex,
as fixing colors by mordants.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stain</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stain
<hw>Stain</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To give or receive a stain; to
grow dim.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stain</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stain
<hw>Stain</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A discoloration by
foreign matter; a spot; <as>as, a <ex>stain</ex> on a garment or
cloth</as>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A natural spot of a color different from the
ground.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Swift trouts, diversified with crimson <qex>stains</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Taint of guilt; tarnish; disgrace;
reproach.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor death itself can wholly wash their <qex>stains</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our opinion . . . is, I trust, without any blemish or
<qex>stain</qex> of heresy.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Cause of reproach; shame.</def> <rj><au>Sir P.
Sidney.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A tincture; a tinge.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You have some <qex>stain</qex> of soldier in you.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Blot; spot; taint; pollution; blemish; tarnish;
color; disgrace; infamy; shame.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stainer</ent>⟦br⟧
